00:40:57,466 --> 00:40:58,740
Yeah, but I like savoury things.

684
00:40:58,826 --> 00:41:01,135
But you said too salty,
which means it's horrible.

685
00:41:01,226 --> 00:41:03,501
- I like crisps.
- Don't ask me any more questions.

686
00:41:03,586 --> 00:41:05,895
- Hello, again.
- MAGGIE: Hey, hello.

687
00:41:05,986 --> 00:41:08,056
- This is my friend Andy.
- Hi.

688
00:41:08,146 --> 00:41:09,864
Hiya. Jon.

689
00:41:09,946 --> 00:41:12,744
- What are you doing here?
- I'm just having lunch.

690
00:41:12,826 --> 00:41:16,660
- That's what we're doing, isn't it?
- Yeah, just letting it cool down here, though.

691
00:41:16,746 --> 00:41:19,101
Having a bit of lunch
just before we go back to work.

692
00:41:19,186 --> 00:41:22,064
- Are you having to work late tonight, then?
- No, not tonight.

693
00:41:22,146 --> 00:41:25,934
I'm going to a drinks do. I don't know
if you know, it's Jackie Greer's birthday.

694
00:41:26,026 --> 00:41:29,860
Oh, my God, I'm going! I'm already going.
Oh, spooky.

695
00:41:29,946 --> 00:41:31,982
I'm sure you're welcome
to come along as well.

696
00:41:32,066 --> 00:41:34,057
I can't, I'm doing anything else.

697
00:41:34,146 --> 00:41:37,024
So do you know Jackie Greer very well,
good friends?

698
00:41:37,106 --> 00:41:40,621
Not really, no. The producer's going down
so he sort of asked us to go along.

699
00:41:40,706 --> 00:41:43,743
- You know, team bonding or whatever.
- The producer of this?

700
00:41:43,826 --> 00:41:47,819
Yeah, Martin the producer. He's going to
be there. He knows Jackie from years back.

701
00:41:47,906 --> 00:41:51,785
Yeah, I'll probably move stuff around.
I might as well come down for a couple of...

702
00:41:51,866 --> 00:41:56,018
Yeah? Okay, we'll see you later on then
for a drink and a bit of a laugh, eh?

703
00:41:56,106 --> 00:41:57,459
That'd be great, yeah.

704
00:41:57,546 --> 00:42:01,744
Yeah, well I'd better get this down me.
Line my stomach. Coq au vin.

705
00:42:02,746 --> 00:42:05,738
- Sounds a bit rude, doesn't it?
- Not really.

706
00:42:05,826 --> 00:42:07,384
What have you gone for?

707
00:42:07,466 --> 00:42:10,936
Oh, boring.
Just three bean salad, spinach and smoothie.

708
00:42:11,026 --> 00:42:15,099
- I'm on a high fibre diet.
- Oh. No bowel cancer for you, then.

709
00:42:17,266 --> 00:42:19,063
Hopefully not, no.

710
00:42:19,706 --> 00:42:22,266
- Okay. See you later.
- See you later, bye.

711
00:42:22,346 --> 00:42:23,665
Bye.

712
00:42:24,506 --> 00:42:26,542
- "No bowel cancer for you, then?"
- All right.

713
00:42:26,626 --> 00:42:28,378
Classic. That's really funny.

714
00:42:34,426 --> 00:42:35,984
- Hi.
- Hello.

715
00:42:36,066 --> 00:42:37,704
- You all right?
- Yes.

716
00:42:37,786 --> 00:42:40,254
- You're not going to...
- No, no, I'm good.

717
00:42:40,346 --> 00:42:43,895
- Good. Well, I got you a gift.
- Why?

718
00:42:43,986 --> 00:42:47,296
Just to say thanks for being part
of this amazing project, you know.

719
00:42:47,386 --> 00:42:48,944
Oh, thank you very much.

720
00:42:49,026 --> 00:42:52,814
And to thank you for the line you said
you'd get me, do you remember?

721
00:42:52,906 --> 00:42:55,136
- Did I?
- Yeah, you probably don't remember

722
00:42:55,226 --> 00:42:58,024
because you were crying
about your dead family and stuff.

723
00:42:58,106 --> 00:43:00,256
But you said you'd ask Ben for a line.

724
00:43:00,346 --> 00:43:03,258
Are you going to ask Ben for a line?

725
00:43:03,346 --> 00:43:05,655
Yes, I can do that.

726
00:43:05,746 --> 00:43:07,976
I didn't know what to get you,
got you vouchers.

727
00:43:08,066 --> 00:43:09,738
- Vouchers?
- Yeah.

728
00:43:09,826 --> 00:43:11,942
Fifteen quids' worth.

729
00:43:12,026 --> 00:43:14,256
- It's like money?
- It's exactly like money

730
00:43:14,346 --> 00:43:16,701
but you can only spend it at Top Shop.

731
00:43:16,786 --> 00:43:20,096
So, you'll ask Ben, yeah?

732
00:43:21,226 --> 00:43:22,454
Yeah.

733
00:43:22,546 --> 00:43:24,935
Brilliant. Fifteen quid.

734
00:43:25,026 --> 00:43:26,903
See you later.

735
00:43:31,226 --> 00:43:32,944
(GUNSHOTS)

736
00:43:34,226 --> 00:43:36,023
(EXPLOSION)

737
00:43:37,946 --> 00:43:39,425
Cut! Cut!

738
00:43:40,066 --> 00:43:43,297
Why is he laughing?
Why are you laughing, hm?

739
00:43:44,546 --> 00:43:46,696
- I tripped up.
- What's so funny?

740
00:43:46,786 --> 00:43:48,458
I tripped up.

741
00:43:48,546 --> 00:43:52,016
Okay. All right, do you think this is funny?

742
00:43:52,466 --> 00:43:54,297
You think war is funny?

743
00:43:54,386 --> 00:43:57,219
Do you think genocide is funny? Huh?

744
00:43:57,746 --> 00:43:59,976
Are you his mum? Yeah. Let me ask you this.

745
00:44:00,066 --> 00:44:03,138
Do you think this'll be funny?
If I shot your mother right now?

746
00:44:03,226 --> 00:44:05,581
If I shot your mummy in the face,
would that make you laugh?

747
00:44:05,666 --> 00:44:07,418
Do you think that would be funny?

748
00:44:07,506 --> 00:44:10,976
If I blew your mother's face off now,
would that make you laugh?

749
00:44:11,066 --> 00:44:13,944
Okay, so maybe you should think
of that next time you trip, okay?

750
00:44:14,026 --> 00:44:16,062
Let's do it right now, let's go.

751
00:44:16,946 --> 00:44:20,382
- BEN: Still rolling.
- And the atrocities continue.

752
00:44:21,386 --> 00:44:22,819
BEN: And action!

753
00:44:22,906 --> 00:44:24,817
It's so itchy, this.

754
00:44:40,306 --> 00:44:42,820
- JACKIE: Maggie and Andy.
- Hi.

755
00:44:47,026 --> 00:44:48,539
- Is that for me?
- Yes.

756
00:44:48,626 --> 00:44:51,902
Thank you so much. I wasn't expecting you,
I thought your sister was ill.

757
00:44:51,986 --> 00:44:55,023
Yes, but it turned out to be
not as serious as we first thought.

758
00:44:55,106 --> 00:44:57,825
So, yeah, women's problems.

759
00:44:58,546 --> 00:45:01,618
Typical, quite a build up.
I had to get out of the house in the end.

760
00:45:01,706 --> 00:45:06,063
I thought she was gonna have my face off.
A Rottweiler with lipstick.

761
00:45:06,146 --> 00:45:07,864
Busy, though.

762
00:45:08,066 --> 00:45:10,455
- You look amazing.
- Thank you.

763
00:45:10,546 --> 00:45:12,901
Someone said the producer was coming.
Is that...

764
00:45:12,986 --> 00:45:15,102
It's Martin, he's over there.

765
00:45:15,186 --> 00:45:16,904
- Oh, okay.
- You look gorgeous.

766
00:45:16,986 --> 00:45:20,023
Look at you, I wouldn't have thought
to put that with that...

767
00:45:28,386 --> 00:45:32,095
...and that's the same problem we've got...

768
00:45:32,706 --> 00:45:33,900
Hello!

769
00:45:33,986 --> 00:45:36,102
- Oh, hello.
- Hi.

770
00:45:36,186 --> 00:45:38,780
No, it was Elaine's idea originally.

771
00:45:38,866 --> 00:45:41,334
He says that every time,
but it was both of us.

772
00:45:41,426 --> 00:45:45,578
It's usually true. Anyway,
it's modern retellings of the old stories

773
00:45:45,666 --> 00:45:47,543
and we're going to make several of them.

774
00:45:47,626 --> 00:45:50,140
It's going to be a little bit like
Kieslowski's Decalogue.

775
00:45:50,226 --> 00:45:51,705
- Have you see those?
- Yes.

776
00:45:51,786 --> 00:45:56,018
Well, you know there's that one character,
the Watcher, and it's a fantastic character.

777
00:45:56,106 --> 00:45:58,336
Have you read that
Kieslowski on Kieslowski book?

778
00:45:58,426 --> 00:45:59,620
No, I haven't.

779
00:45:59,706 --> 00:46:03,016
He wrote later that he was so upset
that he left him out of two of the films

780
00:46:03,106 --> 00:46:04,824
'cause he really wished he was...

781
00:46:04,906 --> 00:46:07,181
It's his fault, should've...

782
00:46:08,146 --> 00:46:11,616
Do you want a drink?
I'm a friend of Jackie's. My round.

783
00:46:11,706 --> 00:46:14,743
- Oh, great, we're on champagne.
- Three glasses of champagne.

784
00:46:14,826 --> 00:46:18,216
- Oh, just get a bottle.
- Yes, definitely.

785
00:46:20,466 --> 00:46:21,694
Anyway, so...

786
00:46:23,666 --> 00:46:25,975
What do you mean,
why have you not seen me around?

787
00:46:26,066 --> 00:46:27,215
I've gone red.

788
00:46:27,306 --> 00:46:29,774
Have you done other productions?
Are you an actress?

789
00:46:29,866 --> 00:46:32,096
- No.
- Oh, you look like you should be an actress.

790
00:46:32,186 --> 00:46:33,938
- Costume dramas or something like that.
- Yeah?

791
00:46:36,946 --> 00:46:39,062
I'd imagine it'll be seconds...

792
00:46:52,146 --> 00:46:53,898
Hi. Andy.

793
00:46:53,986 --> 00:46:55,783
Oh, Andy, yeah. Oh, cheers.

794
00:46:55,866 --> 00:46:56,901
Cheers.

795
00:46:56,986 --> 00:47:01,457
Just thinking what you and Ben
are doing in this film, wonderful,

796
00:47:01,546 --> 00:47:03,616
it moved me, so...

797
00:47:03,706 --> 00:47:05,264
- Thank you.
- No, thank you.

798
00:47:05,346 --> 00:47:08,224
Can I ask you something?
What was your inspiration?

799
00:47:08,306 --> 00:47:10,376
Well, obviously the story.

800
00:47:10,466 --> 00:47:11,694
Oh, yeah.

801
00:47:11,786 --> 00:47:13,981
In film terms. Probably something like the...

802
00:47:14,066 --> 00:47:15,784
- Are you a film buff?
- I adore films.

803
00:47:15,866 --> 00:47:18,664
Well, I'll tell you what I re-watched
when we were planning this.

804
00:47:18,746 --> 00:47:19,735
Oh, please do.

805
00:47:19,826 --> 00:47:22,386
Andrzej Wajda's War Trilogy.
They're extraordinary, aren't they?

806
00:47:22,466 --> 00:47:23,581
Yeah.

807
00:47:23,666 --> 00:47:28,137
Ben's been watching them, particularly in
relation to battle scenes, a lot of Kurosawa.

808
00:47:28,226 --> 00:47:29,739
Oh, okay.

809
00:47:29,826 --> 00:47:33,296
Yeah, particularly in relation
to the kineticism of the mise en scène.

810
00:47:33,386 --> 00:47:35,820
In the film. Yeah, I see.

811
00:47:35,906 --> 00:47:37,339
You a fan? Generally?

812
00:47:37,426 --> 00:47:39,018
- Yes.
- Of Japanese cinema?

813
00:47:39,106 --> 00:47:40,983
- Oh, definitely.
- Oh, well.

814
00:47:41,706 --> 00:47:43,378
Kurosawa's obviously a master.

815
00:47:43,466 --> 00:47:44,740
Yeah, he's number one.

816
00:47:44,826 --> 00:47:47,135
I suppose on a personal level,
I'm more a fan of Ozu.

817
00:47:47,226 --> 00:47:50,980
Me, too, but I think they're both,
they're both big boys.

818
00:47:51,066 --> 00:47:54,217
- The aesthetics are completely different.
- Chalk and cheese, but...

819
00:47:54,306 --> 00:47:57,855
- He tends to knock the camera off.
- And the other one just lets it on.

820
00:47:57,946 --> 00:48:00,255
It was Elaine actually
who turned me on to Ozu.

821
00:48:00,346 --> 00:48:02,576
- Congratulations.
- Yeah, I wasn't really a fan before.

822
00:48:02,666 --> 00:48:04,019
Really?

823
00:48:04,466 --> 00:48:06,218
No, I'm sure you've found this.

824
00:48:06,306 --> 00:48:08,661
You say to someone, "Do you like
Japanese cinema?" and they say,

825
00:48:08,746 --> 00:48:10,145
"No, can't get into it, boring."

826
00:48:10,226 --> 00:48:12,296
And you say,
"Well, do you like the Magnificent Seven?"

827
00:48:12,386 --> 00:48:14,263
- And they say, "Yes."
- Yeah, they like that.

828
00:48:14,346 --> 00:48:17,497
And you think, well,
it's a remake of the Seven Samurai.

829
00:48:17,586 --> 00:48:20,339
Yeah, yeah, course it is.
What, they didn't know that?

830
00:48:20,426 --> 00:48:22,781
- No.
- Seven's the clue. Can't just make that up.

831
00:48:22,866 --> 00:48:25,699
No, it really upsets me.
I want everyone to love the Seven Samurai.

832
00:48:25,786 --> 00:48:30,496
I love all the number films, really.
Seven Samurai, Ocean's Eleven, Dirty Dozen.

833
00:48:30,586 --> 00:48:33,384
Which is about as many as I think
you can have on screen at once.

834
00:48:33,466 --> 00:48:35,980
- But seven is perfect for me.
- Apologies for this,

835
00:48:36,066 --> 00:48:38,660
but I don't really recognise you.
What are you doing?

836
00:48:38,746 --> 00:48:43,376
I'm an actor, yeah. Although at the moment,
I'm concentrating more on background work,

837
00:48:43,466 --> 00:48:46,856
looking out towards getting a speaking role.
In anything.

838
00:48:46,946 --> 00:48:49,904
- Andy, sorry to interrupt.
- Not at all.

839
00:48:49,986 --> 00:48:51,419
Listen, can I have a quick word?

840
00:48:51,506 --> 00:48:53,576
- Not now, I'm a little bit busy.
- Two minutes.

841
00:48:53,666 --> 00:48:56,738
- I'm in the middle...
- Don't mind us. We'll be here.

842
00:48:56,826 --> 00:48:58,657
Yeah? Okay, all right.

843
00:49:02,946 --> 00:49:05,824
I just wanted to let you know that
Jon's going on somewhere else

844
00:49:05,906 --> 00:49:07,544
- and he's asked me to go with him.
- Fine.

845
00:49:07,626 --> 00:49:10,823
I wanted to let you know
because it was me who dragged you here.

846
00:49:10,906 --> 00:49:13,295
You'd be all annoyed
because I'd disappeared...

847
00:49:13,386 --> 00:49:14,899
I'm fine, I'm chatting.

848
00:49:14,986 --> 00:49:16,897
- He's nice.
- He is, yes.

849
00:49:18,946 --> 00:49:21,096
- Foot doesn't bother you?
- Eh?

850
00:49:21,186 --> 00:49:23,905
I know you're a deeply shallow person,
I thought the foot would be a problem.

851
00:49:23,986 --> 00:49:25,055
What do you mean?

852
00:49:25,146 --> 00:49:29,025
He's got one leg shorter than the other, look.
He's wearing one of them big shoes.

853
00:49:29,106 --> 00:49:31,666
- Oh, my God.
- You didn't notice that?

854
00:49:31,826 --> 00:49:34,135
Well, no, it was under the table, wasn't it?

855
00:49:34,226 --> 00:49:36,660
- Yes. Must have been a big table.
- No, don't.

856
00:49:36,746 --> 00:49:38,384
- What?
- I didn't see.

857
00:49:38,466 --> 00:49:42,141
Oh, look at him. He's a lovely man.
He's funny, he's attractive.

858
00:49:42,226 --> 00:49:45,024
Look at him, everybody loves him,
life and soul of the party.

859
00:49:45,106 --> 00:49:47,700
- Certainly the sole.
- Oh, come on.

860
00:49:47,786 --> 00:49:51,256
If you're above it. If you don't mind
being known as Maggie, "Who's Maggie?"

861
00:49:51,346 --> 00:49:54,497
"Maggie, the girl who goes out with
the fellow with the big shoe," that's fine.

862
00:49:54,586 --> 00:49:56,497
But they can do something
about it now, can't they?

863
00:49:56,586 --> 00:49:59,100
- No.
- Some doctor in China or something.

864
00:49:59,186 --> 00:50:02,701
No, it's weird, that's the one thing
they can't do anything about.

865
00:50:02,786 --> 00:50:06,062
They can give you a new face, new heart,
new lungs, new liver, new anything,

866
00:50:06,146 --> 00:50:07,579
but if you go to a doctor and you say,

867
00:50:07,666 --> 00:50:09,861
"Doc, I've got one leg
slightly shorter than the other,"

868
00:50:09,946 --> 00:50:11,584
doesn't matter if you got a million pounds,

869
00:50:11,666 --> 00:50:15,454
they can send you to Switzerland and
all you're coming home with is a big shoe.

870
00:50:15,546 --> 00:50:18,504
- Stop it.
- That's fine, if it's not a problem for you.

871
00:50:18,586 --> 00:50:21,100
I'm not so shallow
that I can't see beyond his big foot.

872
00:50:21,186 --> 00:50:23,984
I know you,
you'll get involved and it will be a problem.

873
00:50:24,066 --> 00:50:26,216
All I'm saying is this,
don't rush off with him tonight.

874
00:50:26,306 --> 00:50:29,184
Sleep on it, if it's not a problem tomorrow,
give him a call.

875
00:50:29,266 --> 00:50:32,736
- In the morning?
- Absolutely, why rush into it now? He's here.

876
00:50:34,106 --> 00:50:36,142
- Hey.
- Hi.

877
00:50:36,226 --> 00:50:38,342
I'm ready to get going if you are.

878
00:50:39,026 --> 00:50:41,381
Now? Right now?

879
00:50:41,906 --> 00:50:44,261
Er... I don't think I can go right now.

880
00:50:45,346 --> 00:50:47,621
Oh, right. You said you fancied it just then.

881
00:50:47,706 --> 00:50:49,936
Yeah, but he just reminded me of something.

882
00:50:50,026 --> 00:50:53,336
- Yeah, I just reminded her.
- I don't think I can go.

883
00:50:54,906 --> 00:50:57,704
Is it... Is it the leg?

884
00:50:59,986 --> 00:51:01,180
Hm?

885
00:51:01,626 --> 00:51:04,857
Is it the fact that I've got one leg
shorter than the other?

886
00:51:06,706 --> 00:51:08,662
- I hadn't noticed.
- You hadn't noticed?

887
00:51:08,746 --> 00:51:10,020
I hadn't.

888
00:51:14,426 --> 00:51:18,260
- You hadn't noticed that?
- Oh! No.

889
00:51:18,426 --> 00:51:21,498
- I hadn't. God, it's a big clumpy one.
- Don't say clumpy.

890
00:51:21,586 --> 00:51:25,545
- It's like a big Herman Munster.
- Oh! Don't say...

891
00:51:26,346 --> 00:51:28,462
- Er...
- Oh, that's...

892
00:51:28,546 --> 00:51:31,185
Do these come in any other styles?

893
00:51:31,306 --> 00:51:33,945
Do you have to buy a pair
and throw one away?

894
00:51:37,346 --> 00:51:39,018
It's been good talking to you.

895
00:51:39,106 --> 00:51:41,859
- Just interested because...
- I've never seen a live one.

896
00:51:41,946 --> 00:51:44,221
Maybe I can phone you tomorrow.

897
00:51:44,306 --> 00:51:48,094
No. No, don't worry about it.
You've shown your true colours.

898
00:51:50,626 --> 00:51:54,175
- That was you.
- It wasn't my fault. How was it my fault?

899
00:51:54,266 --> 00:51:55,858
That poor man.

900
00:51:55,946 --> 00:51:58,983
All his life he's had to deal with people
that are so shallow

901
00:51:59,066 --> 00:52:03,582
that they can't see beyond his foot thing
and he's going to think I'm like that.

902
00:52:03,666 --> 00:52:04,894
You are.

903
00:52:04,986 --> 00:52:07,216
I don't want him to know that.

904
00:52:07,306 --> 00:52:10,662
- Well, don't say Herman Munster then.
- Well, it just slipped out.

905
00:52:10,746 --> 00:52:12,498
Herman Munster just slipped out?

906
00:52:22,506 --> 00:52:23,985
Bit more room.

907
00:52:25,026 --> 00:52:28,655
We were having a conversation earlier
about films, weren't we?

908
00:52:28,746 --> 00:52:30,304
