02:36:17,742 --> 02:36:20,734
Unless you guys disagree with that,
in which case we can change all that.

2695
02:36:20,822 --> 02:36:22,653
- Just do whatever you want to do.
- No.

2696
02:36:22,742 --> 02:36:24,698
No, there's no need to do that.

2697
02:36:24,782 --> 02:36:27,933
What I would say, though,
is because this is your first project,

2698
02:36:28,022 --> 02:36:30,536
I would like you to initially write
with someone else.

2699
02:36:30,622 --> 02:36:32,260
- He will write with anyone.
- I won't.

2700
02:36:32,342 --> 02:36:35,254
He will not write with anyone,
that's a deal breaker.

2701
02:36:35,342 --> 02:36:37,378
No. I'd like to write it myself

2702
02:36:37,462 --> 02:36:40,932
just because it's based on
my own experiences, really.

2703
02:36:41,022 --> 02:36:43,900
The character is based on a boss
I used to work for.

2704
02:36:43,982 --> 02:36:46,701
And I just generally think
the best things are auteured.

2705
02:36:48,102 --> 02:36:49,535
Turd?

2706
02:36:51,662 --> 02:36:52,777
No?

2707
02:36:55,222 --> 02:36:57,782
All right, I'm happy for you
to write it yourself

2708
02:36:57,862 --> 02:37:00,979
but I would feel happier getting Damon
just to work with you as script editor.

2709
02:37:01,062 --> 02:37:04,850
Someone to bounce ideas off, just tidy up
the first script. I think it's a bit flabby.

2710
02:37:04,942 --> 02:37:07,820
Yeah, it's just a bag of ideas at the moment,
but yeah, fine.

2711
02:37:07,902 --> 02:37:12,578
I think the best thing to move this forward
is to get you two together in a little room.

2712
02:37:12,662 --> 02:37:14,653
- Oh!
- Shh!

2713
02:37:16,462 --> 02:37:18,578
Inappropriate at a meeting at the BBC, that.

2714
02:37:18,662 --> 02:37:20,971
- Okay, that would be great.
- Okay.

2715
02:37:21,062 --> 02:37:24,816
Okay, let's talk cash because,
as you know, this script is piping hot.

2716
02:37:24,902 --> 02:37:27,700
- So we're looking for big bucks.
- We don't need to talk cash now.

2717
02:37:27,782 --> 02:37:29,613
We need to talk a little bit about cash.

2718
02:37:29,702 --> 02:37:33,331
Just get some money up front for,
you know, supplies, pencils.

2719
02:37:33,422 --> 02:37:36,300
- I could probably find you a computer.
- You happy with a computer?

2720
02:37:36,382 --> 02:37:38,657
- Yes.
- He's happy with that. We'll go with that.

2721
02:37:38,742 --> 02:37:39,936
Okay, good.

2722
02:37:40,022 --> 02:37:41,501
- You sure you're happy?
- Yes.

2723
02:37:41,582 --> 02:37:43,095
- Thanks.
- Great.

2724
02:37:43,182 --> 02:37:45,457
- Thank you very much.
- Nice to meet you.

2725
02:37:54,182 --> 02:37:57,015
# Celebrate good times, come on #

2726
02:37:57,102 --> 02:37:59,696
Did you get it? Oh, brilliant.

2727
02:37:59,782 --> 02:38:01,454
- Oh, well done!
- Oh, yes.

2728
02:38:01,542 --> 02:38:02,816
Someone's celebrating.

2729
02:38:02,902 --> 02:38:05,860
What, a wealthy old relative
popped her clogs, has she?

2730
02:38:05,942 --> 02:38:07,660
No. So why am I celebrating?

2731
02:38:07,742 --> 02:38:10,779
Could be because of the TV show
the BBC have just given me.

2732
02:38:10,862 --> 02:38:13,660
- TV show?
- Yeah, pilot for a sitcom. So...

2733
02:38:13,742 --> 02:38:16,097
- What sitcom?
- The sitcom I wrote.

2734
02:38:16,182 --> 02:38:19,094
- You're not funny.
- Well, the BBC beg to differ.

2735
02:38:19,182 --> 02:38:22,891
- What's it about?
- It's about my old boss I used to work for.

2736
02:38:22,982 --> 02:38:24,256
Write about what you know.

2737
02:38:24,342 --> 02:38:29,291
I'd just like to say I've got something for you,
just to say thanks for all the great times.

2738
02:38:29,382 --> 02:38:32,419
Just a few crumbs from the table.
Share the wealth.

2739
02:38:32,502 --> 02:38:35,141
I am devastated, really,
to be leaving you lot behind.

2740
02:38:35,222 --> 02:38:37,452
We've had such great...
Especially you, Julie.

2741
02:38:37,542 --> 02:38:39,931
- Lucy.
- Whatever. Shouldn't you be in costume?

2742
02:38:40,022 --> 02:38:41,899
- I am in costume.
- Yeah?

2743
02:38:41,982 --> 02:38:44,815
Why did we never...
And you, will you please call me?

2744
02:38:44,942 --> 02:38:48,332
- I haven't got your number.
- Yeah, 079... (MUMBLING)

2745
02:38:48,422 --> 02:38:50,856
- 07 what?
- Listen up. 0793334...

2746
02:38:50,942 --> 02:38:54,617
All the threes, put them all in otherwise
it doesn't work. And in a particular order.

2747
02:38:54,702 --> 02:38:56,135
- Get it off Julie...
- Lucy.

2748
02:38:56,222 --> 02:38:57,621
- Whatever.
- I haven't got your number.

2749
02:38:57,702 --> 02:38:59,420
- I'll text it to you.
- You haven't got my number.

2750
02:38:59,502 --> 02:39:02,096
I know, but I'll work it out.
Then we'll all have it, won't we?

2751
02:39:02,182 --> 02:39:05,891
Then we can arrange the camping trip
we've always talked about.

2752
02:39:05,982 --> 02:39:08,177
- Anyway, I'll see you later.
- Yeah, okay. Bye.

2753
02:39:08,262 --> 02:39:09,934
See you later, man.

2754
02:39:10,022 --> 02:39:13,856
You all right? You look a bit pale.
Could you get some rouge for Greg?

2755
02:39:13,942 --> 02:39:16,172
- I'm fine.
- You all right? You look a bit sick.

2756
02:39:31,022 --> 02:39:32,614
(LAUGHING HYSTERICALLY)

2757
02:39:45,662 --> 02:39:48,699
I think structurally,
we're all higgledy-piggledy-pew

2758
02:39:48,782 --> 02:39:52,616
and I think we can get to the boss coming in
quicker and set him up straight away.

2759
02:39:52,702 --> 02:39:56,377
Well, we could start with him actually
walking in to work, in the first scene.

2760
02:39:56,622 --> 02:39:58,817
He just actually comes in
and that's when you see him.

2761
02:39:58,902 --> 02:40:02,577
The real Ray used to come in to work
every day without fail.

2762
02:40:02,662 --> 02:40:04,618
He'd just walk up to someone
and say something like,

2763
02:40:04,702 --> 02:40:07,011
"Have you done those invoices?"
And they'd go, "No."

2764
02:40:07,102 --> 02:40:10,492
And he'd go, "Is he having a laugh?
Are you having a laugh?"

2765
02:40:10,582 --> 02:40:12,652
(LAUGHS HYSTERICALLY)

2766
02:40:12,742 --> 02:40:16,451
Brilliant. We're having that.
That's super, that's funny. Do it again.

2767
02:40:16,542 --> 02:40:18,931
That's what he used to do,
just go up to someone

2768
02:40:19,022 --> 02:40:22,935
and go every time, "Is he having a laugh?
Are you having a laugh?"

2769
02:40:23,622 --> 02:40:25,658
That's great. That will be a catchphrase.

2770
02:40:25,742 --> 02:40:28,176
- I'm not sure about catchphrases.
- No, it'll be great.

2771
02:40:28,262 --> 02:40:31,413
People can say it. "Is he having a laugh?
Are you having a laugh?"

2772
02:40:31,502 --> 02:40:34,380
- I just think catchphrases are too easy.
- Are you having a laugh?

2773
02:40:34,462 --> 02:40:36,453
I think it could get a little bit
annoying after a while.

2774
02:40:36,542 --> 02:40:39,739
Do you fancy a coffee?
I haven't had one in about 20 minutes.

2775
02:40:39,822 --> 02:40:42,461
Shall I get one from upstairs
or do you fancy one from Costa's?

2776
02:40:42,542 --> 02:40:45,215
- It might take me a bit longer.
- That one, then.

2777
02:40:45,302 --> 02:40:47,770
Are you having a laugh?

2778
02:40:47,862 --> 02:40:51,537
- Oh, hello. Can we help?
- Hi. It's my friend Maggie. Come in.

2779
02:40:51,622 --> 02:40:53,977
- This is Damon.
- Oh, you cow, I love your bag.

2780
02:40:54,062 --> 02:40:55,211
Oh, thank you.

2781
02:40:55,302 --> 02:40:57,338
I'm just off on a cappuccino run,
do you want one?

2782
02:40:57,422 --> 02:40:59,731
No, it's fine. I'm just here for a wee minute.

2783
02:40:59,822 --> 02:41:02,814
Okay, well, lovely to meet you.
See you again, hopefully.

2784
02:41:02,902 --> 02:41:04,381
- Bye for now.
- Bye.

2785
02:41:04,462 --> 02:41:06,737
DAMON: Oi, Bowker, you poofter!

2786
02:41:06,822 --> 02:41:09,416
- Welcome to our world.
- Look at you.

2787
02:41:09,502 --> 02:41:12,255
- Take a seat. Take a letter.
- I will.

2788
02:41:12,342 --> 02:41:14,014
(MAGGIE GIGGLES EXCITEDLY)

2789
02:41:14,102 --> 02:41:16,980
- Are you well?
- Yeah, well, you know. Got my health.

2790
02:41:17,102 --> 02:41:19,662
- But listen, how's it going here?
- He's doing my head in.

2791
02:41:19,742 --> 02:41:21,141
- Who?
- Who?

2792
02:41:21,222 --> 02:41:24,498
Who? Who do you...
The owner of this monstrosity.

2793
02:41:24,782 --> 02:41:28,934
Quentin Crisp who just skipped down
the corridor going, "I want a cappuccino."

2794
02:41:29,022 --> 02:41:31,661
Oh, he's too gay, he's too gay.

2795
02:41:31,742 --> 02:41:35,132
- What do you mean?
- No one needs to be that gay.

2796
02:41:35,222 --> 02:41:37,816
- What do you mean he's too gay?
- He's a cliché of a gay.

2797
02:41:37,902 --> 02:41:42,373
If I was doing Give us A Clue and
the clue came up "A gay bloke", I'd do him.

2798
02:41:42,462 --> 02:41:46,057
- Unbelievable.
- Well, that's just a wee bit homophobic.

2799
02:41:46,142 --> 02:41:49,976
It's not homophobic.
No, I don't care how much arse sex he has.

2800
02:41:50,062 --> 02:41:52,337
But why does he have to be that camp?

2801
02:41:52,422 --> 02:41:54,652
Screaming and clapping.
When does that happen?

2802
02:41:54,742 --> 02:41:58,018
When do you suddenly think,
"Well, I prefer a nice little saveloy

2803
02:41:58,102 --> 02:42:01,572
"to a battered cod
so I'd better walk like this."

2804
02:42:01,662 --> 02:42:03,937
- I liked him.
- Of course you do.

2805
02:42:04,022 --> 02:42:07,571
- Women like you love the gays.
- What do you mean, women like me?

2806
02:42:07,662 --> 02:42:09,857
Wrong side of 30, six out of ten for looks.

2807
02:42:09,942 --> 02:42:12,410
You've got someone to go to the disco with,
haven't you?

2808
02:42:12,502 --> 02:42:15,414
And you walk in with him and you go,
"No, I'm not sharking, I've got a bloke."

2809
02:42:15,502 --> 02:42:19,415
But if a bloke comes up that you fancy,
you go, "Oh, him? He's just my gay friend."

2810
02:42:19,502 --> 02:42:21,891
- Perfect. It's a safety net.
- Six out of ten.

2811
02:42:21,982 --> 02:42:25,179
- Yeah.
- Is that all I get? Six out of ten?

2812
02:42:25,262 --> 02:42:28,220
- I don't know...
- Look me in the eye and say six out of ten.

2813
02:42:28,302 --> 02:42:30,452
Shall I look you in your wonky eye
or your good eye?

2814
02:42:30,542 --> 02:42:33,614
I have got one eye a wee bit higher up
than the other one.

2815
02:42:36,942 --> 02:42:38,261
- See you.
- Bye.

2816
02:42:38,342 --> 02:42:41,175
I was going to ask you,
how are you getting on with Andy?

2817
02:42:41,262 --> 02:42:44,538
He's lovely, isn't he?
He's very talented. Very funny script.

2818
02:42:44,622 --> 02:42:46,772
You've not run into
any of his funny little ways?

2819
02:42:46,862 --> 02:42:49,740
- No.
- Well, he can be quite odd sometimes.

2820
02:42:49,822 --> 02:42:52,495
I just wanted to let you know
that he is like that with everybody.

2821
02:42:52,582 --> 02:42:55,938
- How do you mean?
- Well, like noise.

2822
02:42:56,022 --> 02:42:57,933
He's got this thing about noise.

2823
02:42:58,022 --> 02:43:00,172
Like, I've seen him at a restaurant,
somebody at the table nearby

2824
02:43:00,262 --> 02:43:03,413
is cutting their meat too loudly and
he's getting himself all annoyed about it.

2825
02:43:03,502 --> 02:43:06,335
Oh, note to self. Cut meat quietly.

2826
02:43:06,422 --> 02:43:10,051
Yes. And you might find you might want
to just tone it down a little bit.

2827
02:43:11,222 --> 02:43:14,294
- Tone what down?
- Well, you're quite camp, which is great,

2828
02:43:14,382 --> 02:43:17,340
but I think maybe sometimes
he thinks you're too gay.

2829
02:43:18,182 --> 02:43:19,695
Did he say that?

2830
02:43:19,782 --> 02:43:22,615
Yeah, but I mean, he wasn't being nasty
about it. I just think...

2831
02:43:22,702 --> 02:43:25,500
Oh, no. I've said the wrong thing.
I shouldn't have, should I?

2832
02:43:25,582 --> 02:43:27,777
No, no, I'm fine. I'm glad you told me.

2833
02:43:27,862 --> 02:43:31,298
Oh, good. Thank God for that.
I thought I'd put my foot in it by telling...

2834
02:43:31,382 --> 02:43:32,895
- Not at all.
- Okay.

2835
02:43:32,982 --> 02:43:36,292
- Well, it was lovely to meet you.
- Absolutely. Lovely to meet you.

2836
02:43:36,382 --> 02:43:38,293
- See you again.
- I'll take it on board.

2837
02:43:38,382 --> 02:43:39,895
Bye.

2838
02:43:47,662 --> 02:43:50,574
You have one message. Message one.

2839
02:43:50,662 --> 02:43:51,811
(BEEP)

2840
02:43:51,902 --> 02:43:55,895
Hello, dear. It's your daddy here, er...
with your mummy.

2841
02:43:55,982 --> 02:43:59,338
- Erm... nothing important.
- MUM: Oh, give it to me.

2842
02:43:59,502 --> 02:44:03,620
Hello, dear. Great news about Andy.
We're so pleased for him.

2843
02:44:03,702 --> 02:44:08,059
And it just got us thinking that maybe you
should try and do something with your life.

2844
02:44:08,182 --> 02:44:11,299
I mean, your dad and I aren't expecting
anything spectacular.

2845
02:44:11,382 --> 02:44:14,260
We were just thinking maybe a wee job
you could be proud of.

2846
02:44:14,342 --> 02:44:17,732
You know, we love you so much,
we hate to think of you growing old

2847
02:44:17,822 --> 02:44:21,610
and being poor and living in squalor
and dying a spinster.

2848
02:44:21,702 --> 02:44:24,296
So, just give us a call
to put our minds at rest

2849
02:44:24,382 --> 02:44:27,374
that you're not just frittering your life away,
would you? Okay?

2850
02:44:27,462 --> 02:44:31,091
And if things get any worse, you can always
come back home. We've still got your room.

2851
02:44:31,182 --> 02:44:33,093
DAD: Well, it's sort of my study now.

2852
02:44:33,182 --> 02:44:36,219
MUM: We could easily squeeze in
a tiny wee single bed.

2853
02:44:36,302 --> 02:44:38,816
All right then, give us a call, sweetheart.
Bye for now.

2854
02:44:38,902 --> 02:44:40,176
DAD: Bye dear.

2855
02:44:40,262 --> 02:44:41,331
Bye.

2856
02:44:43,142 --> 02:44:44,939
(SIGHING)

2857
02:44:46,462 --> 02:44:50,296
Okay, great. Well, I love the changes.
I think this is looking great. Well done.

2858
02:44:50,382 --> 02:44:53,374
- Oh, thank you.
- I think we're ready to move things forward.

2859
02:44:53,462 --> 02:44:57,580
I'd like to shoot a non-broadcast pilot
with a view to making a series.

2860
02:44:57,662 --> 02:45:00,335
Oh! Okay, thank you.

2861
02:45:00,422 --> 02:45:01,935
- All right.
- Brilliant.

2862
02:45:02,022 --> 02:45:04,661
So, are you happy with the way
things have gone so far?

2863
02:45:04,742 --> 02:45:06,778
- Definitely.
- You happy working with Damon?

2864
02:45:06,862 --> 02:45:10,218
- Definitely.
- No problems with the working relationship?

2865
02:45:10,302 --> 02:45:12,941
- Nothing you want to discuss?
- No.

2866
02:45:13,022 --> 02:45:14,421
Okay.

2867
02:45:14,502 --> 02:45:16,777
- I'm not too gay for you, then?
- Damon.

2868
02:45:16,862 --> 02:45:20,013
I'm sorry. I said I wasn't going to say
anything but he's lying through his teeth.

2869
02:45:20,102 --> 02:45:21,854
Excuse me.

2870
02:45:24,382 --> 02:45:27,533
Your friend, Maggie, is it?
She told him what you said about him.

2871
02:45:27,622 --> 02:45:30,090
- What did I say about him?
- That he's too gay.

2872
02:45:30,182 --> 02:45:35,097
- Oh! No. She's an idiot. She's an idiot.
- So you didn't say that?

2873
02:45:35,902 --> 02:45:39,019
Yes, but he wasn't meant to hear it.

2874
02:45:39,782 --> 02:45:43,741
It concerns me if you're so homophobic,
you couldn't work with a gay person...

2875
02:45:43,822 --> 02:45:46,097
No, no, no, no, I'm not homophobic.

2876
02:45:46,182 --> 02:45:48,457
In fact, I actually said to her,

2877
02:45:48,582 --> 02:45:52,621
I said,
"I don't care how much arse sex he has...

2878
02:45:52,702 --> 02:45:56,741
"he's just too..." What was it?
I can't remember what I said.

2879
02:45:57,502 --> 02:45:59,970
You're aware that I'm gay?

2880
02:46:02,062 --> 02:46:03,381
Didn't...

2881
02:46:03,462 --> 02:46:06,295
Well, no, you didn't... And you don't make
a song and dance. You don't go,

2882
02:46:06,382 --> 02:46:08,293
"Ooh, hello! I'm..."

2883
02:46:08,382 --> 02:46:10,498
- No, I didn't.
- I'll stop you there.

2884
02:46:10,582 --> 02:46:11,731
Go on.

2885
02:46:11,822 --> 02:46:14,211
What concerns me is
we've all got to work together

2886
02:46:14,302 --> 02:46:16,133
and if this is where we are
when we've only just started,

2887
02:46:16,222 --> 02:46:18,258
where the hell are we going to be
a month or so down the line?

2888
02:46:18,342 --> 02:46:21,140
It won't be a problem
because I'll just apologise to Damo.

2889
02:46:21,222 --> 02:46:24,612
Everyone gets wound up with
the people they work in close proximity with.

2890
02:46:24,702 --> 02:46:26,579
Little things wind you up,
so it doesn't matter.

2891
02:46:26,662 --> 02:46:30,371
It's not a case of being straight or gay.
It's my neuroses and I'll just, you know...

2892
02:46:30,462 --> 02:46:33,181
Do you think you could put your
hang-ups and your neuroses on hold?

2893
02:46:33,262 --> 02:46:35,332
- Yes.
- He won't be around for long.

2894
02:46:36,502 --> 02:46:38,891
- What, AIDS?
- Sorry?

2895
02:46:39,822 --> 02:46:42,017
Is it AIDS?

2896
02:46:42,142 --> 02:46:44,975
No. I mean the pilot
will only take a couple of months.

2897
02:46:45,062 --> 02:46:46,575
Oh, yeah.

2898
02:46:46,662 --> 02:46:49,859
Right. Listen, talk to Damo, I'll talk to him.

2899
02:46:49,982 --> 02:46:54,021
We'll see where we are and if we feel
we can go forward with this project or not.

2900
02:46:54,102 --> 02:46:57,299
We can... Okay, I'll talk to him.
I'll talk to him now.

2901
02:46:57,382 --> 02:46:59,213
- Okay, good.
- Okay.

2902
02:47:00,382 --> 02:47:02,850
- Okay, I'll go and talk to him.
- All right, bye.

2903
02:47:02,942 --> 02:47:05,297
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

2904
02:47:05,382 --> 02:47:07,657
- Hello.
- Hi. Do me a favour. Stay out of my business.

2905
02:47:07,742 --> 02:47:10,336
- Andy, what? Come in.
- I may have lost the pilot thanks to you.

2906
02:47:10,422 --> 02:47:11,571
- Why?
- Why?

2907
02:47:11,662 --> 02:47:13,539
Because you stuck your nose in
where it wasn't needed.

2908
02:47:13,622 --> 02:47:16,056
Telling Damo I thought he was too gay.
What were you thinking?

2909
02:47:16,142 --> 02:47:18,861
I was thinking that you were stressed
and I just wanted to help you.

2910
02:47:18,942 --> 02:47:22,776
That's helping me, is it?
I just can't believe your stupidity sometimes.

2911
02:47:22,862 --> 02:47:25,695
Andy, don't be like this, I can't cope.
I'm having a bad time at the moment.

2912
02:47:25,782 --> 02:47:27,693
Sorry. What's a bad time for you?

2913
02:47:27,782 --> 02:47:30,091
Tie-dyed the wrong T-shirt?
You lost a kooky broach?

2914
02:47:30,182 --> 02:47:33,413
I was just about getting to where I wanted
to be and you may have fucked it up.

2915
02:47:33,502 --> 02:47:35,458
- I've been grovelling all day at the BBC.
- What do you mean?

2916
02:47:35,542 --> 02:47:38,056
I've got a meeting there at 4:00,
they may pull the plug.

2917
02:47:38,142 --> 02:47:40,610
Imagine if they pull the plug, how am I going
to look you in the face again?

2918
02:47:40,702 --> 02:47:42,374
- Do you want me to say something?
- You're not listening.

2919
02:47:42,462 --> 02:47:45,295
I'm sorry, Andy.
I don't know what you want me to say.

2920
02:47:45,382 --> 02:47:47,896
- I was just trying to help you.
- I don't want you to help me anymore.

2921
02:47:47,982 --> 02:47:51,736
I want you to stop living like a child,
floating through life like everything's okay

2922
02:47:51,822 --> 02:47:53,574
until it actually affects someone, okay?

2923
02:47:53,662 --> 02:47:57,496
So really, my advice to you is,
you've got to grow up.

2924
02:47:58,982 --> 02:48:03,260
Clean up, just sort your own mess out
before you get involved in my life, really.

2925
02:48:36,222 --> 02:48:38,497
- Do you want to follow me?
- Yeah.

2926
02:48:43,902 --> 02:48:46,655
It's unfortunate we've ended up
in this position, Andy.

2927
02:48:46,742 --> 02:48:48,937
I'm not going to speak for Damon.

2928
02:48:49,022 --> 02:48:51,058
Damon, come on.

2929
02:48:51,142 --> 02:48:53,975
- Well, things were said that were very hurtful.
- Yeah.

2930
02:48:54,902 --> 02:48:56,858
But your apology means a lot to me.

2931
02:48:56,942 --> 02:49:01,333
So, if you're happy to work with me,
then I'd like to carry on working with you.

2932
02:49:01,422 --> 02:49:03,333
Definitely. Definitely. Yeah.

2933
02:49:03,422 --> 02:49:05,378
I'm such a huge fan of this project.

2934
02:49:05,462 --> 02:49:07,976
- I'm a big fan of yours, so...
- Great.

2935
02:49:08,062 --> 02:49:09,495
- Happy?
- Definitely.

2936
02:49:09,582 --> 02:49:11,937
- Water under the bridge.
- Wonderful.

2937
02:49:12,422 --> 02:49:15,892
Okay, let's get some dates sorted
and get the ball rolling on his project.

2938
02:49:15,982 --> 02:49:18,860
- Yeah.
- Come on, silly. Huggy Bears.

2939
02:49:21,782 --> 02:49:23,181
DAMON: Now.

2940
02:49:23,262 --> 02:49:24,377
Okay?

2941
02:49:24,462 --> 02:49:25,656
- Do you want one?
- No.

2942
02:49:25,742 --> 02:49:28,495
- Just normal? Okay, brilliant. Okay, thanks.
- Yes.

2943
02:49:31,422 --> 02:49:32,935
Cheers.

2944
02:50:10,022 --> 02:50:11,455
Cut. Great.

2945
02:50:11,542 --> 02:50:13,100
Thank you.

2946
02:50:21,862 --> 02:50:23,773
- See you.
- See you. That's me done.

2947
02:50:23,862 --> 02:50:25,659
- Oh, I'll see you soon.
- Yeah, bye.

2948
02:50:26,662 --> 02:50:27,856
Maggie.

2949
02:50:30,382 --> 02:50:31,781
- Hi.
- You all right?

2950
02:50:31,862 --> 02:50:33,420
Yeah.

2951
02:50:33,502 --> 02:50:35,333
- And you?
- Yeah.

2952
02:50:36,102 --> 02:50:38,013
Here, look.

2953
02:50:40,102 --> 02:50:41,421
Okay, now.

2954
02:50:42,382 --> 02:50:43,781
PATRICK: Hello, Maggie.

2955
02:50:43,862 --> 02:50:46,296
- Hello.
- This is Patrick Stewart here.

2956
02:50:46,382 --> 02:50:49,180
And the reason you're hearing
my rich, sexy voice

2957
02:50:49,262 --> 02:50:52,493
is that Andy is not man enough
to apologise himself,

2958
02:50:52,582 --> 02:50:54,493
even though he knows he's in the wrong.

2959
02:50:54,582 --> 02:50:56,777
That's why he's asked me to do it for him.

2960
02:50:57,462 --> 02:51:02,252
Please, look at his fat, expressionless face.
He doesn't mean any of the things he said

2961
02:51:02,342 --> 02:51:05,095
and he knows you don't have
a malicious bone in your body

2962
02:51:05,182 --> 02:51:07,616
- and were just trying to help.
- Thank you.

2963
02:51:08,662 --> 02:51:11,051
If you can find it in your heart to forgive him,

2964
02:51:11,142 --> 02:51:14,976
then please... make it so.

2965
02:51:17,702 --> 02:51:19,932
Have you seen
Star Trek: The Next Generation?

2966
02:51:20,062 --> 02:51:22,781
Er, no, I haven't, actually.

2967
02:51:22,862 --> 02:51:26,093
Never mind.
Incidentally, Maggie, are you an actress?

2968
02:51:26,182 --> 02:51:28,571
Because I'm writing a film
and I'd love you to be in it.

2969
02:51:28,662 --> 02:51:30,971
Okay. No, she can't. Okay, thanks.

2970
02:51:31,502 --> 02:51:32,696
Cheers.

2971
02:51:32,782 --> 02:51:36,172
- What was that about a film?
- You don't want any part of it, trust me.

2972
02:51:39,102 --> 02:51:41,013
- Your hair looks really nice.
- Shut your face.

2973
02:51:41,102 --> 02:51:43,662
- What? It does.
- Well, thanks.

2974
02:51:43,742 --> 02:51:46,256
- The pilot's fine, by the way.
- Thank God for that.

2975
02:51:47,062 --> 02:51:49,451
I just wanted to let you know
that I have taken on board

2976
02:51:49,542 --> 02:51:52,659
all that stuff that you were saying
about growing up.

2977
02:51:52,742 --> 02:51:55,097
- Oh, don't please, shut up.
- Well, I have.

2978
02:51:55,182 --> 02:51:57,252
- Oh, don't.
- Well, you know what I mean.

2979
02:51:57,342 --> 02:51:59,492
- Well, I'm mortified.
- No, I know, but you were right.

2980
02:51:59,582 --> 02:52:02,494
I wasn't right. You're about the most
grown-up person I know.

2981
02:52:02,582 --> 02:52:05,779
- I'm sort of the only person you know.
- You win by default.

2982
02:52:06,662 --> 02:52:08,300
Correct.

2983
02:52:09,542 --> 02:52:11,180
I'm really sorry.

2984
02:52:11,862 --> 02:52:14,092
Can you let go of my hand, please?

2985
02:52:17,502 --> 02:52:21,734
Of course. Aren't my hands lucky? 'Cause
that would ruin everything, wouldn't it?

2986
02:52:21,822 --> 02:52:24,655
- He's quite a nice one, though, isn't he?
- He's fine.

2987
02:52:24,742 --> 02:52:27,973
I've been working up to saying hello to him
for the last couple of days.

2988
02:52:28,062 --> 02:52:29,814
- Sure.
- What do you think?

2989
02:52:29,902 --> 02:52:31,255
- You know what I think.
- What?

2990
02:52:31,342 --> 02:52:33,253
I think you're a tart.

2991
02:52:33,342 --> 02:52:35,014
Go on, then.

2992
02:52:35,502 --> 02:52:37,220
- Work your magic.
- Yeah, I will.

2993
02:52:37,302 --> 02:52:38,530
I'll see you later, yeah?

2994
02:52:38,622 --> 02:52:40,294
- See you.
- See you.

2995
02:52:49,142 --> 02:52:50,700
ANDY: That was quick.

2996
02:52:50,782 --> 02:52:54,138
I couldn't think of anything witty to say.
He was on the phone anyway.

2997
02:52:55,262 --> 02:52:57,014
ANDY: What would you rather do...

2998
02:52:57,102 --> 02:52:59,696
(MAGGIE LAUGHS) Go on, then.

2999
02:52:59,782 --> 02:53:01,818
Wake up and your teeth
have sort of fallen out,

3000
02:53:01,902 --> 02:53:04,336
wake up and your hair's fallen out,

3001
02:53:04,422 --> 02:53:08,301
or wake up and your toes have fallen off?

3002
02:53:08,382 --> 02:53:09,974
(MAGGIE LAUGHING)

3003
02:53:10,102 --> 02:53:12,616
Er... what, is my hair gone for good?

3004
02:53:12,702 --> 02:53:15,296
(TEA FOR THE TILLERMAN
BY CAT STEVENS)

